    "created_at": "2024-11-09T13:51:52Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-11-09T13:51:52Z",
    "body": "> First, won't the default do the wrong thing with colocated jj repos, since it'll find the .git dir before .jj?\r\n\r\nI want people using `git` not to have to check for `.jj` if they can avoid it, they're the vast majority, which ties with what you said, \"*Might it be better to have only git in the default list*\"; I agree, I'll change it when making my MR.\r\n\r\n> Second, if the cost of checking multiple repos is too high to pay, why should anyone pay it by accident?\r\n\r\nWe already do worse when people activate support for two or more VCSes since both are checked each time instead of stopping at the first one.\r\n\r\n> How bad are the search costs? Could they be parallelized?\r\n\r\nNot bad at all, all VCSes have a directory or file to search for (`.git`, `.jj`, `.pijul`, ...) so in essence it's going up the chain and checking for them and immediately eliminating when there is no such file or directory.\r\n\r\nI can make it so it reuses the same allocation even. The code below takes 1.8ms on my machine (macOS, notably slow FS) for the first run and then at most 600µs, sometime as little as 200µs. Compared to the actual cost when a VCS repo is found and informations have to be parsed, it's absolutely trivial\r\n\r\n```rust\r\n// Uncommented and ugly, in practice I would document this to explain why we reuse the alloc\r\nuse std::path::Path;\r\n\r\nfn main() {\r\n    let a = Path::new(\"/a/long/path/to/the/current/directory\");\r\n    \r\n    let tested = [\r\n        \".git\",\r\n        \".jj\",\r\n        \".pijul\",\r\n    ];\r\n    let longest = tested.into_iter().max_by(|a, b| a.len().cmp(&b.len())).unwrap_or_default();\r\n\r\n    let mut buf = a.join(longest);\r\n    let start = std::time::SystemTime::now();\r\n    for p in a.ancestors() {\r\n        buf.clear();\r\n        buf.push(p);\r\n        buf.push(\"dummy\");\r\n        for t in tested {\r\n            debug_assert!(buf.pop());\r\n            buf.push(t);\r\n            dbg!(&buf);\r\n            if buf.exists() {\r\n                // Do stuff\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n    dbg!(start.elapsed());\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n> Or worse, won't everyone pay the search costs for each VCS in the list, in directories without VC, since Starship will have to check for all of them?\r\n\r\nNo, not if we only activate `git` by default and let people add what they actually use otherwise, so in practice it would only check for `.git` for most people (which starship already does pretty much unconditionally, and in a much costlier way, since the git repo infos are used by several modules, not only git)",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
